# How to draw a line in Field
# before you do anything, you need a box to draw thing in. You get a new "Spline Drawer" from the right click menu. # then we need some code in the box that draws things.
# we need an object Ñ a PLine Ñ to hold the drawing line = PLine()
# then we draw into it line.moveTo(50,50) line.lineTo(100,100)
# having drawn it we need to actually put it on the screen. Each box keeps a list of PLines to draw
_self.lines.clear() # clear any previous lines out _self.lines.add(line) # and add this line

# we can draw lots of different things in similar ways line = PLine()
line.moveTo(50,50)
# curve towards 100,50; curve back towards 70, 130, and then end up at 100,100 line.cubicTo(100,50, 70,130, 100, 100)
# now we translate this line out of the way of the example we have to the left line += Vector2(150,0)
# and then we add it, same as before _self.lines.clear() _self.lines.add(line)

# there are many properties that we can set on lines to change their appearance line = PLine()
line.moveTo(50,50) line.cubicTo(100,50, 70,130, 100, 100) line.lineTo(100, 50).cubicTo(75, 75, 75, 50, 50, 50)
line += Vector2(450,0)
line.filled = 1
# set the color of the line (both the line and the fill) line.color=Color4(0.25, 0, 0, 0.5) #that's a dark red (0.25) that is 50% (0.5) transparent line.thickness=4
# and then we add it same as before _self.lines.clear() _self.lines.add(line)
# but if we copy the line, we can change its appearance line = line.copy() line.strokeColor=Color4(0, 0, 0.25, 0.25) line.fillColor=Color4(0.25, 0, 0, 0.1) line += Vector2(0,30) line += rotation(0.2) _self.lines.add(line)
line = line.copy() #an alternative, compact syntax for setting properties: line(stroked=0, pointed=1, fillColor=Color4(0.25, 0.25, 0, 0.5)) line += Vector2(0,30) line += rotation(0.2) _self.lines.add(line)

# not just lines, also filled shapes line = PLine()
line.moveTo(50,50) line.cubicTo(100,50, 70,130, 100, 100)
# we can chain drawing instructions together line.lineTo(100, 50).cubicTo(75, 75, 75, 50, 50, 50)
# now we translate this line out of the way of the example we have to the left line += Vector2(300,0)
# we tell Field that we want this filled using properties on the line: line.filled = 1
# and then we add it same as before _self.lines.clear() _self.lines.add(line)

# two ways of drawing a dashed line
line = PLine()
line.moveTo(50,50) line.cubicTo(100,50, 70,130, 100, 100) line.lineTo(100, 50).cubicTo(75, 75, 75, 50, 50, 50)
a = line.copy()
# first we can just tell Field that we want to stroke it a particular way when it ends up on the screen
a.strokeType = BasicStroke(1,1,1,1,(4,4),0) # that's a lot of parameters, to get help put the cursor just after BasicStroke and press command-period
a += Vector2(0,150) _self.lines.clear() _self.lines.add(a)
# the second way is to actually stroke the line, and get hold of the new line that's got all of the geometry
b = line.copy()
b.strokeWith(thickness=2, dash=(8,4))
# we'll color this one red b(derived=1, color=Color4(0.5, 0, 0, 1)) b += Vector2(0, 200) _self.lines.add(b)
# with this line we can split it into it's individual segments, and transform them further:
segments = b.segment() for s in segments: s += Vector2(0, 50).noise(10) s(color=Color4(0,0.5, 0, 1)) _self.lines.add(s)
# by overlapping lots of transparent lines get get something textured for n in range(0, 20): c = b.copy() c.strokeWith(thickness=1, dash=(8,4)) segments = c.segment() for s in segments: s += Vector2(0, 100).noise(n*2) s(strokeColor=Color4(0,0, 0, 0.1), derived=1) _self.lines.add(s)

# we've seen properties associated with lines. They can be associated with points Ñ vertices Ñ on lines as well
p = PLine().moveTo(50,50)
# vertex properties end with _v p(strokeColor_v = Color4(1,0,0,1), pointSize_v=20.0)
p.lineTo(100,50) p.lineTo(100,100) p.relCubicTo(10,10,10,-10,50,100) p.lineTo(50,50)
# vertex properties, once set, are interpolated over the line. So we've set the point size, and the strokeColor, at the start and the end of the line, so we end up with a progression of points sizes clockwize in the diagram p(pointSize_v=1.0, strokeColor_v=Color4(0,0,1,1)) p.pointed=1
p+=Vector2(160,160) _self.lines.clear() _self.lines.add(p)

label= """Basic drawing in Field; click on each example for the code""" width=300 opacity=0.5
#---------------------------------------------
from java.awt import Font _self.lines.clear()
text = PLine().moveTo(0,0)(offsetFromSource=Vector2())
text(containsMultilineText=1) text(multilineWidth_v=width) text(text_v=label)
text(font_v=Font("Gill Sans", 0, 15)) text(totalOpacity=opacity)
_self.lines.add(text)
_self.noFrame=1

_self.lines.clear() line = PLine().moveTo(50, 50).lineTo(100,60).polarCubicTo(-1,1,1,-1, 200,150)
# the code so far has already demonstrated a few ways of transforming a PLine (try commenting out all of these transformations and then putting them back in one by one)
# translating it
line += Vector2(850, 550)
# scaling it (around its middle) line *= Vector2(1.5, 1.5)
# scaling it around some other point line *= scale(0.5, around=Vector2(-760, -490))
# copying it anotherLine = line.copy()
# transforming each vertex of it (this reflects it around its middle) line.visitPositions(lambda x,y : Vector2(line.bounds().midpoint2().x*2-x, y))
# transforming each 'node' (which is a vertex and any control vertices near it) def filter(before, now, after, beforeIsCurve, afterIsCurve): if (not before): return if (not after): return middle = (before+after)/2.0 now[:] = (now-middle)*3.4+middle
# this "sharpens" the line line.visitNodes(filter)
# querying the line for information lineCursor = line.cursor()
# line length print lineCursor.length()
# move the cursor to the middle of the line lineCursor.forwardD(lineCursor.length()/2)
def drawPoint(at): _self.lines.add(PLine().moveTo(*at)(pointed=1, color=Color4(1,0,0,0.2), pointSize=10))
# draw this point drawPoint(lineCursor.position())
# split the line at this position into two lines left, right = lineCursor.split()
# scale them both left *= Vector2(1.5, 1.5) right *= Vector2(1.5, 1.5)
# make them red left(color=Color4(1,0,0,0.5), derived=1) right(color=Color4(1,0,0,0.5), derived=1)
# and draw them all _self.lines.add(left) _self.lines.add(right) _self.lines.add(line)

# Drawing lines with code is fun, but sometimes it's tedious to edit them by continually redrafting code over and over again
# Field lets you edit lines with the mouse
_self.lines.clear() for q in range(0, 4): line = PLine().moveTo(50+q*30, 700) line.polarCubicTo(1,1,0,0,100+q*20,900) line.moveTo(*line.position) line.polarCubicTo(1,1,0,0,200+q*5,800) lines = line.segment() for ll in lines: ll*=Vector2(0.6,1) _self.lines.add(ll)
# you click on nodes to select them, and then you can drag them around. Shift clicking lets you change tool, or add nodes.
# this line executes all of the edits that you make with the mouse _self.tweaks()
# what it's actually doing is writing code. It's writing code inside this box, but in a different place. You can what property you are looking at (and editing) in the editor using the drop down box at the top of this window.
# Even after you've edited something, you can write more code to access it.
# here we make 10 random echos of the lines that we are editing for line in ArrayList(_self.lines): line = PLine(line) for n in range(0, 10): line = line.copy() line+=Vector2().noise(20) line+=rotation(Math.random()*0.03) line.visitPositions(lambda x,y : Vector2(x,y).noise(10)) line(color=Color4(0,0,0,0.5/(1+n)), derived=1, thickness=n) _self.lines.add(line)

# Field has three ways of putting text on the canvas, all use the PLine system someLine = PLine() someLine.containsText = 1 someLine.moveTo(800,50) someLine.text_v = "Hello World" # you can put a text label on every vertex of a line (since text_v is a per vertex property) someLine.moveTo(900,25) someLine.text_v = "I'm over" someLine.moveTo(920,46) someLine.text_v = "here" _self.lines.clear() _self.lines.add(someLine)

# The second way of putting text on the canvas is for larger amounts of text that wraps someLine = PLine().moveTo(800,130) someLine.text_v = "Hello World. This is a multiline wrapping piece of text that has html formatting applied to it." someLine.containsMultilineText = 1 # this sets the font from java.awt import Font someLine.font_v = Font("Optima", 0, 20) # this sets the width someLine.multilineWidth_v=400 _self.lines.clear() _self.lines.add(someLine) # if you click carefully on the left hand side of the labels in the canvas (for example the one that says "three ways of doing text") you'll see that we use this method to write them as well Ñ it's all code!

_self.lines.clear()
# The last way of making text actually turns it into geometry (rather than just having text label a vertex)
at = AdvancedTextToCachedLine("Gill Sans", 20)
theText = PLine(at.getLine("Hello World", 800, 250)) _self.lines.add(theText)
# or, more realistically: theText = PLine(at.getLine("Hello World", 800, 300)) theText(filled=1, stroked=1, fillColor=Color4(0.25, 0, 0, 1), strokeColor=Color4(0.25,0,0,0.1), derived=1) _self.lines.add(theText)
# but it's just geometry, so we can transform it theText = PLine(at.getLine("Hello World", 800, 350)) theText(derived=1, filled=1, color=Color4(0,0,0,0.1))
for n in range(0, 10): segments = theText.segment() for s in segments: s += Vector2().noise(n*2) s.visitPositions(lambda x, y : Vector2(x,y).noise(2)) _self.lines.add(s)
